[Stern] Why, Tariq,
I had almost given up hope.

10:38.271 --> 10:40.340
Has your watch stopped?

10:40.374 --> 10:42.409
Young African Americans
have a responsibility

10:42.642 --> 10:44.077
to be prompt, young man.

10:44.111 --> 10:47.180
We must subvert expectations
whenever possible.

10:47.214 --> 10:50.384
Yes, ma'am, I apologize.
I had a family emergency.

10:50.417 --> 10:51.885
[Stern]
Yes, well, I suppose you have

10:51.918 --> 10:54.788
the family emergency
these days, don't you?

10:54.821 --> 10:56.890
He really is
remarkably resilient,

10:56.923 --> 10:58.058
wouldn't you say, Ida?

10:59.659 --> 11:01.962
Tariq, I was surprised
when our esteemed alumnus here

11:01.995 --> 11:03.263
reached out on your behalf

11:03.296 --> 11:05.432
and suggested that you
wanted to matriculate

11:05.665 --> 11:07.701
so soon after
your father's passing.

11:07.734 --> 11:11.371
Are you really ready for the
academic rigors of Stansfield?

11:11.405 --> 11:13.006
[Tariq]
Yes, ma'am, I believe so.

11:13.040 --> 11:15.075
In fact, I think that school
will help distract me

11:15.108 --> 11:17.110
from the things
I'd rather not think about.

11:17.144 --> 11:19.112
I think Stansfield
will be a great refuge

11:19.146 --> 11:20.947
from the outside world for me.

11:20.981 --> 11:23.050
[Brooks] Well, I certainly
understand that, young man.

11:23.083 --> 11:24.951
[Stern] I'm glad to hear
you feel prepared,

11:24.985 --> 11:26.253
because unfortunately,

11:26.286 --> 11:28.722
in exchange for your admission
here at Stansfield,

11:28.755 --> 11:32.292
we've had to add a little extra
to your plate.

11:32.325 --> 11:35.195
We'd like you to tutor
one of our students,

11:35.228 --> 11:36.396
a basketball player.

11:36.430 --> 11:37.764
Do you like basketball?

11:37.798 --> 11:39.099
Of course he likes basketball.

11:39.132 --> 11:41.401
[drawer clatters open]

11:42.903 --> 11:45.372
-Uh, may I?
-Please.

11:45.405 --> 11:46.973
What's the student's name,
ma'am?

11:47.007 --> 11:49.242
Ezekiel Cross.
Have you heard of him?

11:49.276 --> 11:51.445
-Wonderful jump shot.
-No, I haven't.

11:51.478 --> 11:53.747
Well, we've actually
arranged for him

11:53.780 --> 11:56.316
to be your roommate
in the dormitory.

11:56.349 --> 11:57.918
You move tomorrow.

11:57.951 --> 12:01.288
And in which subject will I
be tutoring Ezekiel, ma'am?

12:01.321 --> 12:02.722
All of them.

12:02.756 --> 12:05.792
Zeke doesn't play,
you don't stay.

12:06.493 --> 12:09.262
[Brooks] Now you need to go
meet your advisor.

12:09.296 --> 12:12.265
[dramatic music plays]

12:12.299 --> 12:15.268
♪ ♪

12:15.302 --> 12:16.837
[woman]
You lost?

12:18.772 --> 12:21.141
Oh.
Damn, was it that obvious?

12:21.174 --> 12:23.009
Yeah, a little bit.

12:23.043 --> 12:24.778
What building
are you looking for?

12:24.811 --> 12:26.313
Um, University Hall.

12:26.346 --> 12:27.881
I'm headed that way.

12:29.049 --> 12:30.250
What year are you?

12:30.283 --> 12:32.018
Freshman.

12:32.052 --> 12:35.021
Wait, are you gonna take
Canonical Studies?

12:35.055 --> 12:36.389
I'm not sure.

12:36.423 --> 12:39.226
I'm supposed to be meeting
someone named Caridad Milgram.

12:39.259 --> 12:41.161
She's my
"minority student counselor."

12:41.194 --> 12:44.197
Yeah, she's mine too.
Most of the freshmen have her.

12:44.231 --> 12:47.300
But Professor Milgram
also teaches Canonical Studies.

12:47.334 --> 12:49.503
It'd be nice to have another
Black kid in there with us.

12:49.536 --> 12:51.204
There's only, like, four now.

12:51.238 --> 12:53.273
What do you mean "like, four"?

12:53.306 --> 12:56.143
Everyone who's Black
isn't Black, you know?

12:56.176 --> 12:57.811
Really willing to own it.

12:57.844 --> 12:59.880
Speaks up when
the white kid oversteps.

12:59.913 --> 13:02.082
Right now, you got me,
this one girl BruShaundria,

13:02.115 --> 13:03.950
and this other guy Khalid.

13:03.984 --> 13:05.819
And then there's Richard.
[sighs]

13:05.852 --> 13:07.254
It's like he was
dipped in chocolate

13:07.287 --> 13:08.822
but the inside doesn't match.

13:08.855 --> 13:10.157
[Tariq chuckles]

13:10.190 --> 13:12.359
I'm guessing you're not too shy
about your opinion, huh?

13:12.392 --> 13:13.994
What would be
the point of that?

13:14.961 --> 13:17.898
University Hall is the next
building to your right.

13:17.931 --> 13:21.034
You'll get used to this place
pretty fast, I promise.

13:21.067 --> 13:22.235
See you around.

13:23.170 --> 13:25.238
Hey, wait.
What's your name?

13:25.272 --> 13:26.473
I'm Tariq.

13:26.506 --> 13:28.241
Lauren.

13:28.275 --> 13:30.210
I hope to see you in class.

13:30.243 --> 13:33.213
[soft music plays]

13:33.246 --> 13:35.015
♪ ♪

13:35.048 --> 13:37.284
[tense percussive music plays]

13:37.317 --> 13:39.119
Oh, fuck.

13:40.120 --> 13:42.556
[Carrie] It can be hard
for students of color at first

13:42.589 --> 13:44.558
at Stansfield.

13:44.591 --> 13:46.593
I mean, my own mother
struggled here

13:46.826 --> 13:48.562
as a young Black woman
in the late '70s.

13:48.595 --> 13:50.430
And as an interracial couple,
well,

13:50.463 --> 13:53.466
my parents were still
an anomaly.

13:53.500 --> 13:55.068
But times have changed, and...

13:55.101 --> 13:58.004
well, the school's
now invested in our concerns.

13:59.105 --> 14:00.240
You know, I don't understand

14:00.273 --> 14:01.942
why the dean wanted me
to come see you.

14:01.975 --> 14:04.211
I've been going to all-white
schools my whole life.

14:05.912 --> 14:09.082
Well, I'm sure she thought
your personal circumstances

14:09.115 --> 14:10.917
required extra support.

14:10.951 --> 14:13.086
Um, "my personal
circumstances"?

14:13.119 --> 14:14.554
Your parents, Tariq.

14:14.588 --> 14:16.223
Your father's
unfortunate death,

14:16.256 --> 14:17.624
your mother's arrest.

14:27.634 --> 14:30.403
You can talk to me...

14:30.437 --> 14:32.005
about anything.

14:33.039 --> 14:34.274
How are you feeling?

14:34.307 --> 14:35.909
Look, my parents, I think,

14:35.942 --> 14:37.577
would want me to concentrate
on my schoolwork.

14:37.611 --> 14:40.547
And I heard you teach something
called Canonical Studies,

14:40.580 --> 14:43.383
and I read in the course
catalog that in that class,

14:43.416 --> 14:45.151
the students
get to graduate early.

14:46.486 --> 14:49.389
Well, the level of difficulty
for Canonical Studies

14:49.422 --> 14:51.291
is very high, Tariq.

14:51.324 --> 14:56.062
Course credit is double that
of a normal freshman workload.

14:56.096 --> 14:58.431
Students can elect to graduate
after their third year,

14:58.465 --> 15:00.467
but most choose not to do so.

15:00.500 --> 15:03.169
You just got here.

15:03.203 --> 15:05.272
Why are you
in such a hurry to leave?

15:06.106 --> 15:09.175
I have to help my grandmother
with my baby sister.

15:09.209 --> 15:10.944
I have to help my family.

15:12.145 --> 15:17.017
Canonical Studies requires
a verbal entrance exam...

15:18.285 --> 15:22.022
...on this book,
The Stranger by Camus.

15:23.256 --> 15:25.058
Okay, so when can I
take the test?

15:26.126 --> 15:28.161
Professor Milgram,
I'm not asking

15:28.194 --> 15:29.663
for any special treatment.

15:31.031 --> 15:33.199
I'm asking not to lose
an opportunity.

15:35.068 --> 15:37.470
The DA has agreed
to four years' probation

15:37.504 --> 15:39.306
for criminally negligent
homicide

15:39.339 --> 15:41.574
with all the other charges
included.

15:42.609 --> 15:44.010
No jail time?

15:44.044 --> 15:45.445
[Tameika]
No jail time.

15:45.478 --> 15:48.982
Somebody wants your husband's
secret life to stay a secret.

15:49.015 --> 15:52.118
You allocute tomorrow morning
accurately and specifically,

15:52.152 --> 15:54.521
and you go home
tomorrow afternoon.

15:55.422 --> 15:56.956
How can I ever thank you?

15:56.990 --> 15:58.692
[Tameika]
Thank your husband's ambition.

15:58.725 --> 16:01.094
If he hadn't gotten in bed
with politicians,

16:01.127 --> 16:03.997
we'd be stuck
with that man two charge.

16:04.030 --> 16:07.334
There is one last thing with
Quinton Wallace's testimony.

16:07.367 --> 16:09.202
He said you rushed him
out the door.

16:09.235 --> 16:10.670
You were on a schedule.

16:10.704 --> 16:12.172
You arrived
at the precise moment

16:12.205 --> 16:13.440
where James would be alone--

16:13.473 --> 16:15.508
no guests,
no security detail.

16:15.542 --> 16:17.110
How did you know?

16:18.211 --> 16:19.412
What does that matter?

16:19.446 --> 16:21.748
If your story isn't airtight,

16:21.981 --> 16:23.450
the prosecutor
can ask you questions

16:23.483 --> 16:25.018
right there
in front of the judge.

16:25.051 --> 16:28.254
If that happens for any reason,
we have to be prepared.

16:28.288 --> 16:30.156
How did you know James
would be alone?

16:30.690 --> 16:32.659
[Tasha] When he gets in the
elevator to the loading dock,

16:32.692 --> 16:35.195
you text me
and let me know.

16:35.695 --> 16:38.631
[Tameika]
It's an allocution under oath.

16:38.665 --> 16:41.601
You cannot lie.
What are you not telling me?

16:41.634 --> 16:43.503
I'm telling you everything.

16:43.536 --> 16:46.139
No, you must have had a cue.

16:46.172 --> 16:49.743
Someone else was there.
Someone told you he was alone.

16:50.610 --> 16:52.345
You gotta be gone by then.

16:52.379 --> 16:54.080
Okay, I will be.

16:54.114 --> 16:55.515
No, nothing like that.

16:55.548 --> 16:57.584
[Tameika]
I can't suborn perjury, Tasha.

16:57.617 --> 16:59.786
If you lie and they prove it,

17:00.019 --> 17:02.756
you will go to jail,
and I will lose my license.

17:02.789 --> 17:06.025
If you had an accomplice,
you have to tell me who it is.

17:06.059 --> 17:08.261
They might come forward.
They might expose you.

17:08.294 --> 17:09.295
That won't happen.

17:09.329 --> 17:11.498
[Tameika]
How can you be so sure?

17:11.531 --> 17:14.501
[dramatic music plays]

17:14.534 --> 17:16.236
Is it your son?

17:17.737 --> 17:19.339
No.

17:21.540 --> 17:23.376
You are my client.

17:23.410 --> 17:25.111
I can't let you lie for Tariq.

17:25.145 --> 17:26.279
I can't let you
go to jail for him.

17:26.311 --> 17:28.047
-Tameika, you're fired.
-What?

17:28.080 --> 17:29.382
Tasha, you will lose
your deal.

17:29.416 --> 17:31.317
Get out!

17:31.351 --> 17:33.486
I mean it. Go.

17:33.520 --> 17:36.489
[tense music plays]

17:36.523 --> 17:39.526
♪ ♪

17:42.061 --> 17:43.830
[pounding on door]

17:44.063 --> 17:46.699
[door clicks open]

17:46.733 --> 17:49.736
♪ ♪

17:52.105 --> 17:53.573
Hello?

17:53.606 --> 17:56.209
[Tameika] Tariq,
this is Tameika Washington.

17:56.242 --> 17:58.178
Hey, Ms. Washington.
What'd they say about my mom?

17:58.211 --> 17:59.379
Did she get a deal?

17:59.412 --> 18:01.147
I don't know what's gonna
happen to your mom.

18:01.181 --> 18:02.549
She just fired me.

18:02.582 --> 18:04.117
Wait, what?

18:04.150 --> 18:05.218
You told me all she had to do

18:05.251 --> 18:06.586
was tell them
exactly what happened.

18:06.619 --> 18:09.389
That's exactly right,
but she won't.

18:09.422 --> 18:11.224
She won't tell the truth.

18:11.257 --> 18:13.326
She is protecting someone,
Tariq.

18:13.359 --> 18:15.261
I think you might know
who it is.

18:15.295 --> 18:18.264
♪ ♪

18:18.298 --> 18:19.699
What did she say?

18:20.567 --> 18:21.835
Nothing.

18:21.868 --> 18:23.670
And even if she
told me everything,

18:23.703 --> 18:25.205
our conversations
are privileged,

18:25.238 --> 18:26.706
and I can't say a word
to anyone.

18:26.739 --> 18:29.275
Without me, Tariq, your mom
is in a lot of trouble.

18:29.309 --> 18:32.212
You're gonna need to get her
a good attorney fast,

18:32.245 --> 18:33.813
someone who doesn't need
the truth to win.

18:33.847 --> 18:36.216
What lawyer doesn't need
the truth to win?

18:37.584 --> 18:41.888
Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury, my client...

18:42.121 --> 18:43.790
[chuckles]

18:43.823 --> 18:48.661
...Mr. William Ryan,
has been railroaded

18:48.695 --> 18:51.698
by his colleagues,
his board of directors,

18:51.731 --> 18:54.801
and, in fact,
the US Attorney's Office.

18:54.834 --> 18:58.238
He's a scapegoat,
the classic fall guy.

18:58.271 --> 19:00.673
Innocent as the day
he was born,

19:00.707 --> 19:04.377
trusting as his parents
raised him to be,

19:04.410 --> 19:06.546
he fell for the oldest trick
in the book.

19:06.579 --> 19:07.714
But instead

19:07.747 --> 19:11.184
of the red-hot shame
of the fool,

19:11.217 --> 19:16.155
his innocence has led him
to the cold, hard steel

19:16.189 --> 19:18.424
of the shackle.

19:18.458 --> 19:19.559
Look at my client.

19:19.592 --> 19:21.861
[dramatic music plays]

19:21.895 --> 19:24.297
Does he look like
he needs to steal?

19:25.698 --> 19:28.668
[triumphant music plays]

19:28.701 --> 19:30.837
♪ ♪

19:30.870 --> 19:32.705
-Davis MacLean?
-Oh, no, no, no, kid.

19:32.739 --> 19:34.374
I'm in a rush.
I got a meeting across town.

19:34.407 --> 19:35.708
I do not have time
for pictures.

19:35.742 --> 19:36.910
I don't want a picture.

19:36.943 --> 19:37.944
My mother's on trial
for killing my father,

19:38.177 --> 19:39.178
and I want to hire you.

19:41.314 --> 19:42.882
St. Patrick.

19:42.916 --> 19:44.384
Your James St. Patrick's son.

19:44.417 --> 19:45.818
That was a good picture
of you in The Times

19:45.852 --> 19:47.186
next to his obituary.

19:47.220 --> 19:49.389
Classic African-American
family,

19:49.422 --> 19:51.925
you know, except for the wife
with the smoking gun.

19:51.958 --> 19:53.693
My mother's innocent.

19:53.726 --> 19:55.929
Yeah, I'm sure
that's what she told you,

19:55.962 --> 19:59.432
but you should accept the fact
that she's going to jail

19:59.465 --> 20:01.734
and you get to start
your life over again.

20:01.768 --> 20:03.369
Oh.

20:03.403 --> 20:04.938
Don't let your parents
define you.

20:04.971 --> 20:06.873
You can be anything
that you want to be,

20:06.906 --> 20:09.742
and that advice
I'll give you for free.

20:09.776 --> 20:11.978
I said I wanted to hire you.
How much?

20:12.211 --> 20:14.414
-You don't have it.
-How much?

20:14.447 --> 20:16.282
Five hundred K,
liquid, up front.

20:16.316 --> 20:17.917
You get that, we'll talk.

20:17.951 --> 20:20.920
[determined music plays]

20:20.954 --> 20:23.890
♪ ♪

20:23.923 --> 20:26.459
[Estelle] Tariq,
we need to start planning

20:26.492 --> 20:27.627
your daddy's funeral.

20:28.728 --> 20:30.697
Tariq.

20:30.730 --> 20:32.699
Tariq, are you all right?

20:34.300 --> 20:36.636
Boy, look at me
when I'm talking to you.

20:37.904 --> 20:40.473
Listen...

20:40.506 --> 20:42.875
I know that you gotta
talk to somebody,

20:42.909 --> 20:46.245
and I know... baby, I know
that you're hurting.

20:46.279 --> 20:48.548
Just talk to me.

20:48.581 --> 20:49.983
Grandma, I have to get back
to school.

20:50.016 --> 20:52.452
I have an oral exam
in the morning.

20:52.485 --> 20:54.988
All right, then just stay
the night, okay?

20:55.021 --> 20:56.589
Because your sister needs you.

20:56.623 --> 20:58.725
You both need me, Grandma!

20:58.758 --> 20:59.792
You guys need me
to finish school

20:59.826 --> 21:01.260
so I can get my inheritance

21:01.294 --> 21:03.496
so I can help you, Ma, and Yas.

21:06.432 --> 21:08.434
Whatever happens with Ma.

21:09.035 --> 21:11.471
Grandma, if you really
want to help me, help me look.

21:12.772 --> 21:14.407
Is this the only place
that Ma kept the books

21:14.440 --> 21:15.475
from the day care?

21:15.508 --> 21:17.644
Yeah, yeah, that's everything.

21:17.677 --> 21:21.414
Why?
What are you looking for?

21:21.447 --> 21:22.615
-[telephone ringing]
-Get the phone.

21:25.652 --> 21:28.621
[dark music plays]

21:28.655 --> 21:31.424
♪ ♪

21:31.457 --> 21:33.292
Hello?

21:33.326 --> 21:36.429
Yes, I'll accept the charges.

21:36.462 --> 21:37.630
Yasmine.

21:37.664 --> 21:40.667
Come here and talk
to your mommy.

21:40.700 --> 21:41.968
[Yasmine]
Hi, Mommy.

21:42.001 --> 21:44.537
[Estelle] Yeah, actually,
he's here right now.

21:44.570 --> 21:45.805
You want to talk to him?

21:45.838 --> 21:47.573
Tariq?

21:48.908 --> 21:50.343
Your mother.

21:51.911 --> 21:53.346
Hey, Ma.

21:53.379 --> 21:54.414
You okay?

21:54.447 --> 21:56.082
Yeah.

21:56.315 --> 21:58.685
Um, I'm okay.
I'm okay, 'Riq.

21:58.718 --> 22:01.054
Grandma, can I speak
to her alone?

22:01.087 --> 22:02.955
I don't understand
why I can't listen

22:02.989 --> 22:04.891
when the guards can.

22:04.924 --> 22:07.627
♪ ♪

22:15.601 --> 22:17.336
Ma, why'd you fire Tameika?

22:19.439 --> 22:21.708
-How'd you hear about that?
-She called me.

22:21.741 --> 22:23.109
We need to get you
a new lawyer.

22:23.342 --> 22:26.979
No, I'm fine.
I have a public defender.

22:27.013 --> 22:29.015
I'll figure everything out.
Don't worry.

22:29.048 --> 22:30.783
[sighs]

22:32.985 --> 22:34.353
You think any of the parents
from the day care

22:34.387 --> 22:35.521
still need help?

22:35.555 --> 22:36.656
Remember that one lady

22:36.689 --> 22:37.857
you used to tell me about?

22:37.890 --> 22:39.859
She used to come
pick up her son late?

22:39.892 --> 22:41.761
She worked this weird job
at night?

22:41.794 --> 22:43.996
No, listen to me.

22:44.030 --> 22:45.398
Tariq, you don't need to worry

22:45.431 --> 22:48.401
about opening up
the day care again, okay?

22:48.434 --> 22:49.736
What I need

22:49.769 --> 22:52.705
is for you to concentrate
on school, all right?

22:52.739 --> 22:55.074
If you take care of yourself,
you'll take care of all of us.

22:55.108 --> 22:57.076
Tariq, do you hear me?

22:57.110 --> 23:00.646
I need you to promise me
that you'll focus on school.

23:02.949 --> 23:04.484
Yeah, I promise, Ma.

23:05.818 --> 23:08.554
[sighs]
Okay. I love you.

23:08.588 --> 23:11.591
♪ ♪

23:27.607 --> 23:30.610
[indistinct chatter]

23:32.945 --> 23:34.447
-Jabari--
-Hey, uh, what is this

23:34.480 --> 23:36.048
about another student interview
tomorrow morning?

23:36.082 --> 23:37.650
It showed up on my schedule,
but I thought we were done.

23:37.683 --> 23:38.985
Tariq St. Patrick.

23:39.018 --> 23:40.887
His father
was James St. Patrick,

23:40.920 --> 23:42.522
the candidate
for lieutenant governor.

23:42.555 --> 23:46.459
His mom is on trial
for the murder.

23:46.492 --> 23:48.895
I've been assigned
as his counselor.

23:48.928 --> 23:51.130
He's really motivated
to do the work.

23:51.164 --> 23:53.166
This kid was in high school
two weeks ago.

23:53.199 --> 23:54.834
He was squeezed in
by a booster.

23:54.867 --> 23:56.536
He's rich, connected.

23:56.569 --> 23:58.204
He doesn't need us
to bend over backwards for him.

23:58.437 --> 23:59.906
Canonical Studies is closed.

23:59.939 --> 24:02.108
You know, I would have thought
you of all people

24:02.141 --> 24:03.676
would want to help this kid.

24:03.709 --> 24:04.844
Why, because he's Black?

24:04.877 --> 24:06.546
Yes, and because
he can't help having

24:06.579 --> 24:08.915
unique circumstances
getting here.

24:08.948 --> 24:11.017
So what
he's not from the hood?

24:11.050 --> 24:13.619
Does that mean he doesn't pass
your blackness litmus test?

24:13.653 --> 24:15.188
[chuckles]
So you're telling me

24:15.221 --> 24:16.956
if the same kid came in
with the same story

24:16.989 --> 24:19.525
but he was white, you expect us
to change the rules?

24:19.559 --> 24:21.594
We already have enough
white students in the class.

24:21.627 --> 24:23.529
True, but he's already
a whole week behind,

24:23.563 --> 24:24.831
and this course is rigorous,

24:24.864 --> 24:26.833
and do you think Oliver
is gonna sign off on this?

24:26.866 --> 24:30.169
Well, if we both argue for it,
he won't have a choice.

24:30.203 --> 24:32.638
Don't make this
about you and me.

24:32.672 --> 24:34.006
It's not.

24:34.040 --> 24:36.742
And as you like to say,
there is no you and me,

24:36.776 --> 24:37.910
not anymore.

24:39.145 --> 24:40.713
At least meet him.

24:41.547 --> 24:42.515
Fine.

24:42.548 --> 24:43.783
If he impresses me,

24:43.816 --> 24:45.518
then I will help you
make the argument to Oliver,

24:45.551 --> 24:46.552
but he won't.

24:50.223 --> 24:53.192
[muffled hip-hop music
playing]

24:53.226 --> 24:56.229
♪ ♪

24:58.965 --> 25:00.800
Where I know you from?

25:00.833 --> 25:03.069
You used to keep your son
at my mom's day care.

25:03.102 --> 25:05.071
Right, Tasha's place.
That's where I met you.

25:05.104 --> 25:07.607
Ain't you a little young
to be getting in here?

25:07.640 --> 25:09.075
I'm not here for that.

25:09.108 --> 25:10.209
I was wondering
if you was willing

25:10.243 --> 25:11.677
to make some extra money.

25:11.711 --> 25:12.845
Listen, I already
told your mama

25:12.879 --> 25:15.081
that the block is hot
around her, okay?

25:15.114 --> 25:17.750
-My mom is in jail right now.
-For real?

25:17.783 --> 25:19.819
But not for drugs.

25:19.852 --> 25:21.754
They think she shot my father.

25:21.787 --> 25:24.090
[sucks teeth] A bitch
gotta start watching the news.

25:24.123 --> 25:25.691
That's crazy.

25:25.725 --> 25:28.628
Okay, so listen, I owe your
mother, so I'll help you out,

25:28.661 --> 25:31.564
but you gotta find
your own product, okay?

25:31.597 --> 25:33.065
All right, I gotta go
'cause Cinnamon be stealing

25:33.099 --> 25:34.767
all the good body glitter
and shit.

25:34.800 --> 25:35.768
[chuckles]

25:35.801 --> 25:38.804
♪ ♪

25:41.641 --> 25:42.775
[hip-hop music playing
over stereo]

25:42.808 --> 25:44.210
[Brayden] Yo,
so my friend's here, people.

25:44.243 --> 25:45.912
So I gotta go.
Say hi, 'Riq.

25:45.945 --> 25:47.246
Man, get that shit
out of my face.

25:47.280 --> 25:48.714
[Brayden] 'Riq's feeling
camera shy, y'all,

25:48.748 --> 25:50.616
but I'll be back
in the Bray-Den tomorrow.

25:50.650 --> 25:52.585
Stay thirsty, my friends.

25:52.618 --> 25:54.820
Bro, what the fuck
are you doing at Stansfield?

25:54.854 --> 25:56.923
I go here; everyone
in my family goes here.

25:56.956 --> 25:58.824
Check this shit out.

26:01.060 --> 26:02.561
[Tariq] Oh, shit.

26:02.595 --> 26:03.963
Your family built
the auditorium?

26:03.996 --> 26:05.965
And the swimming pool.
My brother's a water polo dude.

26:05.998 --> 26:07.133
[whispering]
He's a douchebag.

26:07.166 --> 26:08.701
Listen, let's not
talk about that shit.

26:08.734 --> 26:09.802
That shit's boring.

26:09.835 --> 26:11.337
You know what we need
to talk about

26:11.570 --> 26:12.838
is how many girls
we're gonna get

26:12.872 --> 26:14.206
now that we're both here!

26:14.240 --> 26:15.608
-[laughs]
-Crazy ass.

26:15.641 --> 26:17.009
I figure we work
a kind of old-school,

26:17.043 --> 26:18.110
interracial buddy comedy thing.

26:18.144 --> 26:20.012
You know, you're like
Danny Glover--

26:20.046 --> 26:21.280
Black, serious.

26:21.314 --> 26:23.049
And I'm like Mel Gibson
but not drunk.

26:23.082 --> 26:25.017
-You know what I mean?
-Yeah, man, whatever.

26:25.051 --> 26:26.152
I just got a lot of work to do.

26:26.185 --> 26:27.286
Got an entrance exam

26:27.320 --> 26:29.221
for the Canonical Studies
tomorrow, so...

26:29.255 --> 26:30.656
Canonical Studies?

26:30.690 --> 26:32.191
Damn, I wouldn't even
try that shit.

26:32.224 --> 26:33.926
People fail out of that
all the time.

26:33.960 --> 26:35.194
College is supposed
to be fun, bro.

26:35.227 --> 26:37.196
What are you doing?

26:37.229 --> 26:39.098
You are right about that.

26:39.131 --> 26:40.866
But I don't got that much time
to have fun, bro.

26:40.900 --> 26:42.268
Plus, I gotta move soon,

26:42.301 --> 26:44.737
so I'll hit you later,
if anything.

26:44.770 --> 26:46.672
All right.

26:46.706 --> 26:48.174
Listen, I'm really glad

26:48.207 --> 26:50.076
that we're both here together,
you know?

26:50.109 --> 26:52.244
The shit that went down
between you and Effie

26:52.278 --> 26:54.680
was so fucked up,
and I was really hoping

26:54.714 --> 26:56.716
that we would connect again
and be bros, you know?

26:56.749 --> 27:00.186
About Effie, you still happen
to have her number?

27:00.219 --> 27:02.154
[Brayden]
She got into Yale, man.

27:02.188 --> 27:03.656
[gate buzzes]

27:04.991 --> 27:06.792
[gate squeaks]

27:08.794 --> 27:10.663
So you came
all the way down here.

27:11.697 --> 27:14.000
You must really need
this product or something.

27:14.033 --> 27:15.801
Or maybe you just wanted
to see me.

27:17.136 --> 27:18.738
I need the product.

27:19.972 --> 27:21.874
Yeah, I deserve that.

27:23.342 --> 27:24.977
Are you okay, though?

27:25.778 --> 27:27.146
I heard about your parents.

27:28.314 --> 27:30.349
Look, if you need someone
to talk to, Tariq,

27:30.383 --> 27:32.018
I'm here,
and I'll listen to you.

27:32.051 --> 27:34.353
Now, why the fuck
should I trust you, huh?

27:34.387 --> 27:36.022
You ruined
my whole life, Effie.

27:36.055 --> 27:37.056
You ain't need to move pills
at Choate.

27:37.089 --> 27:38.290
That was a hobby to you.

27:38.324 --> 27:40.126
I couldn't even buy books.

27:41.360 --> 27:43.162
I had to take out
the competition.

27:44.296 --> 27:46.932
It wasn't personal, okay?
It was just business.

27:56.275 --> 27:58.010
So you were just playing me
this whole time, huh?

27:58.044 --> 27:59.111
All of that?

27:59.145 --> 28:00.379
Not the part
about liking you, okay?

28:00.413 --> 28:01.447
That was real.

28:05.951 --> 28:07.953
So you're not gonna
pay me for that?

28:09.255 --> 28:11.157
It's nothing personal, Effie.

28:11.190 --> 28:13.192
It's just business.

28:13.225 --> 28:16.195
[soft dramatic music plays]

28:16.228 --> 28:19.231
♪ ♪

28:26.372 --> 28:27.440
[inhales sharply]

28:27.473 --> 28:30.443
[tense music plays]

28:30.476 --> 28:33.479
♪ ♪

28:40.019 --> 28:42.154
[Carrie]
Tariq, there you are.

28:42.188 --> 28:44.190
I'm so sorry I'm late,
Professor Milgram.

28:44.223 --> 28:45.191
Tariq St. Patrick.

28:45.224 --> 28:47.193
Jabari Reynolds.

28:47.226 --> 28:48.794
I'm Oliver Simmons, Tariq.

28:48.828 --> 28:50.763
Professor Milgram told us
all about you.

28:50.796 --> 28:52.765
She didn't forecast
you'd be late, of course.

28:52.798 --> 28:54.066
I apologize.

28:54.100 --> 28:57.736
Well, let's begin.
Uh, please take a seat.

28:57.770 --> 29:00.739
[uneasy music plays]

29:00.773 --> 29:03.776
♪ ♪

29:04.844 --> 29:07.813
[Jabari] Well, first of all,
did you enjoy the book?

29:08.848 --> 29:11.350
You know, I don't think he
wrote the book to be enjoyed.

29:12.318 --> 29:14.186
Uh, what do you mean?

29:14.920 --> 29:17.756
Well, it wasn't written
in that way.

29:17.790 --> 29:19.959
Because the main character
was sort of bored,

29:19.992 --> 29:22.094
I feel Camus wanted us
to be bored as well.

29:25.364 --> 29:26.532
What'd you think of the end?

29:26.765 --> 29:28.167
That certainly isn't boring.

29:31.170 --> 29:33.139
What-what-what part, sir?

29:35.374 --> 29:36.942
When he attacks the priest.

29:36.976 --> 29:39.011
Professor Milgram,
don't help.

29:41.280 --> 29:42.915
[sighs]

29:42.948 --> 29:45.084
All right,
I didn't finish the book.

29:45.117 --> 29:47.253
♪ ♪

29:47.286 --> 29:51.323
Uh, thanks for telling
the truth, I suppose.

29:51.357 --> 29:54.293
♪ ♪

29:54.326 --> 29:57.062
But honestly, I don't really
relate to the main character.

29:57.096 --> 29:59.031
He shoots someone
for no reason,

29:59.064 --> 30:01.100
and we're supposed to be
sympathetic to that?

30:01.133 --> 30:03.169
And we're supposed
to relate to that?

30:03.202 --> 30:05.137
I mean, I don't.

30:05.171 --> 30:06.505
He has his reasons, of course,

30:06.539 --> 30:08.507
but the book
doesn't give it to us.

30:08.541 --> 30:10.876
I think you missed the point.

30:10.910 --> 30:12.578
It's hard to get the point
if you don't finish the book.

30:12.811 --> 30:13.846
[Jabari]
Amen to that.

30:13.879 --> 30:15.948
I'm sorry
I didn't finish the book.

30:15.981 --> 30:17.216
Hey, I want to do this work,

30:17.249 --> 30:19.318
and I want to be challenged
in this way.

30:19.351 --> 30:21.487
I want to make you guys proud.

30:21.520 --> 30:24.423
I just... I just didn't
have enough time.

30:26.225 --> 30:28.394
Well, that was
a waste of time.

30:28.427 --> 30:31.397
Professor Milgram, next time
you feel the need for charity,

30:31.430 --> 30:33.966
maybe you should donate
to the Red Cross.

30:33.999 --> 30:37.203
Hey, Oliver, look, I didn't say
I was off this kid entirely.

30:37.236 --> 30:38.470
You're not?

30:38.504 --> 30:40.339
It takes a lot of balls
to come in here and say

30:40.372 --> 30:41.574
you didn't like the book
we asked you to read.

30:41.607 --> 30:44.009
Balls are not what I look for
in a student.

30:44.043 --> 30:45.611
No, but maybe you should.

30:45.844 --> 30:47.980
We want to teach new thinkers,
passionate thinkers,

30:48.013 --> 30:49.848
the greatest minds
of our next generation.

30:49.882 --> 30:53.118
-That was a great mind to you?
-Well, it could be.

30:53.152 --> 30:55.854
He has been through
extensive trauma in his life

30:55.888 --> 30:58.324
and in the last month,
and he's still here,

30:58.357 --> 31:00.025
and he still read the book.

31:00.059 --> 31:01.560
[both]
He didn't finish the book!

31:01.594 --> 31:04.396
Okay, fair,
but he got it 24 hours ago.

31:04.430 --> 31:07.967
His mother is on trial
for his father's murder.

31:08.000 --> 31:10.936
I don't know what else
he had to do yesterday.

31:10.970 --> 31:12.871
Do you?

31:12.905 --> 31:15.507
I think we should give him
another shot.

31:15.541 --> 31:17.209
[gate buzzes]

31:23.415 --> 31:26.585
Ms. Green,
I am so sorry I'm late.

31:26.619 --> 31:29.288
I have a lot of other clients.
My name is Dana Patterson.

31:29.321 --> 31:30.489
I'm your public defender.

31:30.522 --> 31:31.957
Can you get me the same deal
Tameika did?

31:31.991 --> 31:34.059
What deal was that?

31:34.093 --> 31:35.361
It's not mentioned here
in your paperwork.

31:35.394 --> 31:36.629
[Jenny]
Funny thing about that deal.

31:36.662 --> 31:38.530
It went out the window
along with your story

31:38.564 --> 31:40.399
about you being the shooter.

31:40.432 --> 31:42.001
Forensics just came back.

31:42.034 --> 31:44.470
Whoever shot your husband was
between 5'11" and 6'2" tall.

31:44.503 --> 31:46.438
So unless you were standing
on a ladder,

31:46.472 --> 31:47.973
Ms. Green,
you didn't pull the trigger.

31:48.007 --> 31:49.675
Okay, so if you know my client
didn't kill her husband,

31:49.908 --> 31:51.076
why is she still in here?

31:51.110 --> 31:52.478
Quinton Wallace--
we know Tasha set him up

31:52.511 --> 31:54.313
to take the fall
for this murder.

31:54.346 --> 31:55.514
Accessory after the fact, okay.

31:55.547 --> 31:57.316
No, Dana, she started
that plan in motion

31:57.349 --> 31:59.084
while James St. Patrick
was still alive,

31:59.118 --> 32:01.553
so it's conspiracy one,
plus aiding and abetting,

32:01.587 --> 32:03.088
plus the gun possession charge,

32:03.122 --> 32:04.189
which is all we'll charge

32:04.223 --> 32:06.292
if she gives us the name
of the shooter.

32:06.325 --> 32:07.660
What kind of time?

32:07.693 --> 32:10.129
She can plead on conspiracy,
15 years.

32:10.162 --> 32:11.330
What?

32:11.363 --> 32:12.665
If you don't give us
the name of the shooter

32:12.698 --> 32:14.500
and we do go to trial,
we can charge you with murder.

32:14.533 --> 32:16.468
Just give me the name.

32:16.502 --> 32:19.138
You already lied to me once,
Ms. Green.

32:19.171 --> 32:20.973
Don't do it again.

32:21.006 --> 32:23.275
[Dana]
I think you should cooperate.

32:23.309 --> 32:26.211
[tense music plays]

32:26.245 --> 32:28.047
Andre Coleman.

32:28.080 --> 32:29.581
He wanted my husband dead.

32:29.615 --> 32:32.251
He said he would help me.
It was his gun.

32:33.085 --> 32:35.721
I'll check out
your Coleman story, Ms. Green.

32:35.954 --> 32:37.489
Dana, we'll be in touch.

32:37.523 --> 32:39.391
[Dana] Okay, Jenny.
Love the dress. [laughs]

32:39.425 --> 32:41.960
-[door slams]
-[Dana] Okay, um...

32:41.994 --> 32:45.531
I know ten to 15 years
sounds like a lot,

32:45.564 --> 32:49.335
but it's not gonna get better
than this, I promise.

32:49.368 --> 32:52.304
Why did you fire
Tameika Washington, by the way?

32:52.338 --> 32:54.640
I hear she's really good.

32:54.673 --> 32:57.142
Sorry, I just
need you to sign...

32:57.176 --> 32:59.311
So sorry, I am j...
I am having a day.

32:59.345 --> 33:01.580
[Dana chuckles]

33:04.717 --> 33:07.119
John, what the fuck
you doing here?

33:07.152 --> 33:08.320
Who's this guy?

33:08.354 --> 33:09.488
[Mak] Well, we're hearing
some disturbing news

33:09.521 --> 33:11.590
about the James St. Patrick
case.

33:11.623 --> 33:13.225
I thought it was federal,

33:13.258 --> 33:14.727
but I heard you kicked it
over to the locals.

33:14.760 --> 33:16.695
[scoffs]
Excuse me, sir.

33:16.729 --> 33:18.364
I don't know who you are,
but I'm not sure we should be

33:18.397 --> 33:20.432
discussing prosecutorial
discretion in front of you.

33:20.466 --> 33:22.167
I'm Steven Ott, DNC,

33:22.201 --> 33:23.569
and I was a prosecutor
for 15 years

33:23.602 --> 33:25.170
before I left to work
for the party,

33:25.204 --> 33:26.572
so I think I can keep up.

33:26.605 --> 33:28.607
Yeah, doesn't explain what
you're doing here in my office.

33:28.640 --> 33:30.109
It's important
to the Democratic Party

33:30.142 --> 33:32.778
that certain details
about James St. Patrick's life

33:33.011 --> 33:34.179
not come out in court.

33:34.213 --> 33:35.347
[scoffs]

33:35.381 --> 33:37.149
I don't know
what that has to do with me.

33:37.182 --> 33:39.151
Well, Tasha's using a
justification defense, Cooper.

33:39.184 --> 33:41.220
She's saying
that James St. Patrick

33:41.253 --> 33:43.122
was a drug-dealing
homicidal monster.

33:43.155 --> 33:44.390
Yeah, he was.

33:44.423 --> 33:45.691
Yeah, well,
we see it differently.

33:45.724 --> 33:47.159
[chuckles]
Okay.

33:47.192 --> 33:49.561
You-you know,
I-I'm-I'm-I'm sorry, John.

33:49.595 --> 33:50.729
What game are we playing here?

33:50.763 --> 33:52.798
Well, Steven and I,
we have an idea.

33:53.031 --> 33:55.100
We'd like you to charge
Tasha St. Patrick

33:55.134 --> 33:57.069
under the Kingpin Statute.

33:57.102 --> 33:59.405
Well, Queenpin in this case,
I guess.

34:00.205 --> 34:02.775
We got a friendly judge
to sign over an arrest warrant.

34:02.808 --> 34:04.143
For what?

34:04.176 --> 34:06.044
For running
St. Patrick's organization.

34:06.078 --> 34:08.614
Drug trafficking, murder,
assaults, the whole thing.

34:08.647 --> 34:10.716
I mean, you wanted to build
a RICO, there it is.

34:10.748 --> 34:12.650
St. Patrick's murder
is the predicate crime

34:12.684 --> 34:14.319
that can open this whole thing
right up.

34:14.353 --> 34:17.156
You say she was silencing
the ex-husband as a witness.

34:17.188 --> 34:18.524
You could hang
the whole thing on her.

34:18.556 --> 34:21.460
But she isn't the head
of this organization.

34:22.494 --> 34:24.530
She knew what he was doing.
She's an accomplice.

34:24.563 --> 34:26.231
But she was never the boss.

34:27.132 --> 34:29.435
Gentlemen, I'd love
to help you, but I can't.

34:29.467 --> 34:32.471
St. Patrick roughed Tasha up
the night before she shot him.

34:32.504 --> 34:34.206
I saw the bruises myself.

34:34.239 --> 34:36.775
It's a local case,
a domestic.

34:36.809 --> 34:39.077
I gotta let the DA handle it.

34:39.110 --> 34:40.279
[Ott]
Huh.

34:40.312 --> 34:42.447
Okay.

34:45.284 --> 34:48.286
You know you owe me,
Mr. US Attorney.

34:48.320 --> 34:50.522
Yeah, you think
about that, okay?

34:50.556 --> 34:53.525
I got you this job,
and I can take it away.

34:55.527 --> 34:56.495
[door clicks shut]

34:56.527 --> 34:59.498
[muffled hip-hop music playing]

34:59.531 --> 35:02.534
♪ ♪

35:09.775 --> 35:11.610
-[Tariq] Oh, shit.
-[Shanisha] You ain't lock it?

35:11.643 --> 35:13.345
[Tariq] Yo, my bad.
My bad, bro.

35:13.378 --> 35:15.214
Hey, you my new roommate,
Tariq?

35:15.247 --> 35:17.583
Yeah, I am, but I can come back
if you need me to.

35:17.616 --> 35:20.118
-I'll be done in a minute.
-You better not be.

35:20.152 --> 35:21.753
Can he leave, please?

35:21.787 --> 35:24.389
Hey, uh--
hey, give me 15 minutes.

35:25.257 --> 35:26.325
[mouthing words]

35:26.358 --> 35:28.460
-[Shanisha moans]
-[Tariq] Got you.

35:28.494 --> 35:31.497
♪ ♪

35:34.600 --> 35:37.603
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

35:45.244 --> 35:46.745
[sighs]

35:46.778 --> 35:48.280
Oh, God.

35:51.783 --> 35:55.320
-[Cameron] Oh, look at that.
-[soft laughter]

35:55.354 --> 35:58.657
-Beautiful, Mom, as usual.
-It's Nancy's favorite.

35:59.424 --> 36:02.828
Mom, I am the US Attorney
for the Eastern District now.

36:02.861 --> 36:05.898
I was hoping we'd stop
with that idiotic nickname.

36:05.931 --> 36:07.766
-No way.
-It's not gonna happen.

36:07.799 --> 36:09.167
[Cameron] I don't even remember

36:09.201 --> 36:10.168
what your real name is,
to be honest, Nancy.

36:10.202 --> 36:11.537
Jesus, if Claire were here,

36:11.570 --> 36:12.838
she would say something
on my behalf.

36:12.871 --> 36:14.706
[Courtney] Oh, you mean
your favorite sister?

36:14.740 --> 36:15.841
Well, I'll do it.
[chuckles]

36:15.874 --> 36:19.278
Guys, we should all honor
Cooper's pronouns

36:19.311 --> 36:21.413
of he, him, and his

36:21.446 --> 36:25.617
and that he identifies
as a cis heterosexual male

36:25.651 --> 36:29.354
and that using
a traditionally feminine name

36:29.388 --> 36:32.591
could be viewed
as an intentional assault

36:32.624 --> 36:34.960
on his gender identity.

36:35.193 --> 36:37.596
[Cameron] That's exactly
what she would have said.

36:37.629 --> 36:38.830
That was good.

36:38.864 --> 36:40.399
[Martin] All right, kids,
leave your brother alone.

36:40.432 --> 36:42.501
You've made it
through a hard year, Coop,

36:42.534 --> 36:43.969
and we're all proud of you.

36:44.202 --> 36:45.971
Before we eat,
let's raise a glass

36:46.204 --> 36:47.472
to your brother,

36:47.506 --> 36:50.576
US Attorney
Cooper Andrew Saxe,

36:50.609 --> 36:52.311
returning the family name

36:52.344 --> 36:53.745
to public service.

36:53.779 --> 36:54.746
To Coop.

36:54.780 --> 36:57.382
[all]
To Nancy.

36:57.416 --> 36:59.718
[Martin]
I am proud of you boys.

36:59.751 --> 37:02.321
You're both doing so well.

37:02.354 --> 37:03.455
Good night.

37:04.856 --> 37:05.958
[Saxe] Night, Dad.

37:08.860 --> 37:10.462
-Actually...
-[door clicks shut]

37:10.495 --> 37:12.798
...our general counsel is gonna
retire in a few months.

37:12.831 --> 37:14.666
You should take the job
at our fund, Nancy.

37:14.700 --> 37:16.735
[scoffs]
Fuck you.

37:16.768 --> 37:19.371
I just got a new job,
or did you forget

37:19.404 --> 37:21.807
the entire purpose
of this evening?

37:21.840 --> 37:23.475
Oh, no, I didn't forget.

37:23.508 --> 37:25.711
It's just... US Attorney?

37:25.744 --> 37:27.012
Ooh, it's a lot of pressure.

37:27.245 --> 37:28.847
[both chuckle]

37:28.880 --> 37:32.384
And historically, you don't
do well under pressure.

37:32.417 --> 37:34.953
You and I both know
you're gonna screw this up,

37:34.987 --> 37:37.389
but this time, Dad's emotions
are all involved.

37:37.422 --> 37:39.791
You heard him,
a return to service.

37:39.825 --> 37:41.860
But you've probably
already made the bonehead move

37:41.893 --> 37:43.962
that's gonna get you fired,
embarrass Mom and Dad,

37:43.996 --> 37:45.397
and ruin the family name.

37:45.430 --> 37:48.867
I should punch you
in your smug, bullshit face.

37:48.900 --> 37:50.402
You're my little brother.

37:50.435 --> 37:52.771
I do not need you
to give me a job.

